{{Redirect|Cease and Desist|the Alice Glass song|Cease and Desist (song)}}
A '''cease and desist''' letter is a document sent to an individual or business to stop purportedly illegal activity ("cease") and not to restart it ("desist"). The letter may warn that if the recipient does not discontinue specified conduct, or take certain actions, by deadlines set in the letter, that party may be sued.<ref>Gold, Michael Evan. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ny5Gv2wr3_MC&pg=PA17 An Introduction to Labor Law]'', p. 17 (Cornell University Press, 1998).</ref><ref name="Trimble">{{cite journal |last=Trimble |first=Marketa |year=2010 |title=Setting Foot on Enemy Ground: Cease-and-Desist Letters, DMCA Notifications and Personal Jurisdiction in Declaratory Judgment Actions |url=http://scholars.law.unlv.edu/facpub/105 |journal=[[IDEA: The Intellectual Property Law Review]] |volume=50 |issue=4 |pages=777–830 |accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref> When issued by a public authority, a cease and desist letter, being "a warning of impending judicial enforcement",<ref>{{cite book|last=Lorch|first=Robert Stuart|title=Democratic Process and Administrative Law|year=1980|publisher=Wayne State University Press|page=158|isbn=9780814315132}}</ref> is most appropriately called a "cease and desist order".
Although cease and desist letters are not exclusively used in the area of [[intellectual property]], such letters "are frequently utilized in disputes concerning intellectual property and represent an important feature of the intellectual property law landscape".<ref name="Trimble"/> The holder of an intellectual property right such as a [[copyright]]ed work, a [[trademark]], or a [[patent]], may send the cease and desist letter to inform a third party "of the right holders' rights, identity, and intentions to enforce the rights". The letter may merely contain a licensing offer or may be an explicit threat of a lawsuit. A cease and desist letter often triggers [[licensing]] negotiations, and is a frequent first step towards [[litigation]].<ref name="Trimble"/>
Receiving numerous cease and desist letters may be very costly for the recipient. Each claim in the letters must be evaluated, and it should be decided whether to respond to the letters, "whether or not to obtain an attorney's opinion letter, prepare for a lawsuit, and perhaps initiate [in case of letters regarding a potential patent infringement] a search for alternatives and the development of design-around technologies".<ref name="Trimble"/>
Cease and desist letters are sometimes used to [[intimidation|intimidate]] recipients and can be "an effective tool used by corporations to chill the critical speech of [[gripe sites]] operators". A company owning a [[trademark]] may send such letter to a gripe site operator alleging a [[trademark infringement]], although the actual use of the trademark by the gripe site operator may fall under a [[Fair use (U.S. trademark law)|fair use]] exception (in compliance with, in the U.S., the protection of free speech under the [[First Amendment]]).<ref name="braswell">{{cite journal |last=Braswell |first=Rachael |year=2007 |title=Consumer Gripe Sites, Intellectual Property Law, and the Use of Cease-and-Desist Letters to Chill Protected Speech on the Internet |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/iplj/vol17/iss4/10/ |journal=[[Fordham Intell. Prop. Media & Ent. L.J.]] |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=1241–1287 |accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref>
